Parsedate
=========

just a little helper to rectify some little shortcoming of the built in rails date parsing, like 29.2.2000 is not a valid date and produces a parse error instead of validation error.

the plugin methods take the parameters as argument and removes the associated parts (1i),(2i),etc from the parameters. the date or time will be put int the parameters, the return value is the error string or nil in case of no error.

the usage is still a bit unhandy, but . . . 

Example
=======

with default value

     parsetime(params, :time, time.now)


without default
	
     parsedate(params, :date, time.now)

